<h2 id="content">Introduction</h2>
<p>The development of effective antibiotic therapy has likely prevented hundreds of millions of 
infection-related deaths, but the evolution and spread of multidrug-resistant pathogens 
critically threatens this situation. The population-wide projected impact of antimicrobial resistance has 
been estimated to cost trillions of dollars with considerable increases in morbiditiy 
and mortality from infectious diseases. The Harvard Antimicrobial Resistance (HAMR) GSAS Network 
was founded to bring together the broader Harvard community to address this challenge on all fronts, from 
basic science to population health. Our work falls under two areas: community engagement and political advocacy.</p>
